<doc id="372395" wikidata="Q7700713" url="?curid=372395" title="Tensor product of algebras">
<text>In mathematics, the tensor product of two algebras over a commutative ring &quot;R&quot; is also an &quot;R&quot;-algebra. This gives the tensor product of algebras. When the ring is a field, the most common application of such products is to describe the product of algebra representations.

==Definition==
Let &quot;R&quot; be a commutative ring and let &quot;A&quot; and &quot;B&quot; be &quot;R&quot;-algebras. Since &quot;A&quot; and &quot;B&quot; may both be regarded as &quot;R&quot;-modules, their tensor product
:formula_1
is also an &quot;R&quot;-module. The tensor product can be given the structure of a ring by defining the product on elements of the form by
:formula_2
and then extending by linearity to all of . This ring is an &quot;R&quot;-algebra, associative and unital with the identity element given by . where 1&quot;A&quot; and 1&quot;B&quot; are the identity elements of &quot;A&quot; and &quot;B&quot;. If &quot;A&quot; and &quot;B&quot; are commutative, then the tensor product is commutative as well.

The tensor product turns the category of &quot;R&quot;-algebras into a symmetric monoidal category.

==Further properties==
There are natural homomorphisms from &quot;A&quot; and &quot;B&quot; to given by
:formula_3
:formula_4
These maps make the tensor product the coproduct in the category of commutative &quot;R&quot;-algebras. The tensor product is &quot;not&quot; the coproduct in the category of all &quot;R&quot;-algebras. There the coproduct is given by a more general free product of algebras. Nevertheless, the tensor product of non-commutative algebras can be described by a universal property similar to that of the coproduct:
:formula_5
where [-, -] denotes the commutator.
The natural isomorphism is given by identifying a morphism formula_6 on the left hand side with the pair of morphisms formula_7 on the right hand side where formula_8 and similarly formula_9.

==Applications==
The tensor product of commutative algebras is of frequent use in algebraic geometry. For affine schemes &quot;X&quot;, &quot;Y&quot;, &quot;Z&quot; with morphisms from &quot;X&quot; and &quot;Z&quot; to &quot;Y&quot;, so &quot;X&quot; = Spec(&quot;A&quot;), &quot;Y&quot; = Spec(&quot;R&quot;), and &quot;Z&quot; = Spec(&quot;B&quot;) for some commutative rings &quot;A&quot;, &quot;R&quot;, &quot;B&quot;, the fiber product scheme is the affine scheme corresponding to the tensor product of algebras:
:formula_10
More generally, the fiber product of schemes is defined by gluing together affine fiber products of this form.

==Examples==

* The tensor product can be used as a means of taking intersections of two subschemes in a scheme: consider the formula_11-algebras formula_12, formula_13, then their tensor product is formula_14, which describes the intersection of the algebraic curves &quot;f&quot; = 0 and &quot;g&quot; = 0 in the affine plane over C.
*More generally, if formula_15 is a commutative ring and formula_16 are ideals, then formula_17, with a unique isomorphism sending formula_18 to formula_19.
* Tensor products can be used as a means of changing coefficients. For example, formula_20 and formula_21.
* Tensor products also can be used for taking products of affine schemes over a field. For example, formula_22 is isomorphic to the algebra formula_23 which corresponds to an affine surface in formula_24 if &quot;f&quot; and &quot;g&quot; are not zero.
* Given formula_25-algebras formula_15 and formula_27 whose underlying rings are graded-commutative rings, the tensor product formula_28 becomes a graded commutative ring by defining formula_29 for homogeneous formula_30, formula_31, formula_32, and formula_33.

